havior-changes\">AppleInsider</a>), saying the behavior of VPN On Demand would be different from expected starting with iOS 6.1, and the changes would come in an update that will be released this April.</p><p>\"Due to a lawsuit by VirnetX, Apple will be changing the behavior of VPN On Demand for iOS devices using iOS 6.1 and later,\" Apple wrote. \"This change will be distributed in an update later this month.\"</p><p>The changes are relatively minor—devices with VPN On Demand configured to \"always\" will instead behave as if they're set up to \"establish [a connection] if needed.\" Apple says the device in question will then only establish a new VPN On Demand connection if it's not able to resolve the DNS of the host it wants to reach (these settings can currently be found within Settings &gt; General &gt; VPN).</p></div><p><a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apple-says-vpn-changes-coming-in-ios-thanks-to-virnetx-verdict/#p3n\">Read 3 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apple-says-vpn-changes-coming-in-ios-thanks-to-virnetx-verdict/?comments=1\">Comments</a></p><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:F7zBnMyn0Lo\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~4/3Xu7wjw4a04\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~3/3Xu7wjw4a04/" (20830 64653) new 2 nil nil ((title nil "Apple says VPN changes coming in iOS thanks to VirnetX verdict") (link nil "http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~3/3Xu7wjw4a04/") (comments nil "http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apple-says-vpn-changes-coming-in-ios-thanks-to-virnetx-verdict/#comments") (pubDate nil "Fri, 05 Apr 2013 16:32:13 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Jacqui Cheng") (category nil "Infinite Loop") (category nil "apple") (category nil "FaceTime") (category nil "iOS") (category nil "iOS 6.1") (category nil "patent") (category nil "VirnetX") (category nil "VPN") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://arstechnica.com/?p=240319") (description nil "The changes will be distributed as part of an iOS update later this month.") (content:encoded nil "<div id=\"rss-wrap\"><p>Apple has been forced to change how iOS devices use VPN following a $368.2 million patent verdict in favor of patent and research firm VirnetX. The company wrote about the changes in a <a href=\"http://support.apple.com/kb/TS4550?viewlocale=en_US&amp;locale=en_US\">support document posted to its website</a> on Thursday (hat tip to <a href=\"http://appleinsider.com/articles/13/04/05/apples-loss-to-virnetx-forces-vpn-behavior-changes\">AppleInsider</a>), saying the behavior of VPN On Demand would be different from expected starting with iOS 6.1, and the changes would come in an update that will be released this April.</p><p>\"Due to a lawsuit by VirnetX, Apple will be changing the behavior of VPN On Demand for iOS devices using iOS 6.1 and later,\" Apple wrote. \"This change will be distributed in an update later this month.\"</p><p>The changes are relatively minor—devices with VPN On Demand configured to \"always\" will instead behave as if they're set up to \"establish [a connection] if needed.\" Apple says the device in question will then only establish a new VPN On Demand connection if it's not able to resolve the DNS of the host it wants to reach (these settings can currently be found within Settings &gt; General &gt; VPN).</p></div><p><a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apple-says-vpn-changes-coming-in-ios-thanks-to-virnetx-verdict/#p3n\">Read 3 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apple-says-vpn-changes-coming-in-ios-thanks-to-virnetx-verdict/?comments=1\">Comments</a></p><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:F7zBnMyn0Lo\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=3Xu7wjw4a04:42OfXRXavfI:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~4/3Xu7wjw4a04\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apple-says-vpn-changes-coming-in-ios-thanks-to-virnetx-verdict/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apple-says-vpn-changes-coming-in-ios-thanks-to-virnetx-verdict/"))) ("Apple’s “iRadio” reportedly close to launch, yet labels still have to sign" "<div id=\"rss-wrap\"><p>The \"iRadio\" <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2012/10/apple-reportedly-marching-on-with-pandora-like-music-service-for-2013/\">rumor</a> is back, and there are new details on how Apple hopes to generate more revenue for music studios than competing services. According to sources who spoke to <a href=\"http://news.cnet.com/8301-13579_3-57578062-37/for-labels-apples-iradio-deal-could-be-sweeter-than-pandora/\">CNET</a>, Apple's rumored streaming service would offer users a quick way to buy songs through iTunes, \"potentially boosting download sales,\" in addition to offering a revenue share on audio ads.</p><p>CNET's report claims that Apple is close to striking a deal with two of the four major music labels, Warner Music and Universal Music Group. That suggests EMI and Sony Music are apparently <em>not</em> close to a deal with Apple, despite the fact that the company has supposedly informed the labels that it wants to have an agreement hammered out in time for a summer launch. The report notes that Apple would also need to get the music publishers on board before launching its Pandora-like streaming service.</p><p>The element that appears to be holding back the labels is Apple's decision to weigh its payment structure on ad revenue instead of the more traditional per-play rate. \"The only thing concrete in the contract is the per-play rate,\" one unnamed source told CNET. \"If you end up having no ad revenue, that's still zero. And we won't know what the buying habits will be. Will people streaming still take the time to buy from iTunes?\"</p></div><p><a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apples-iradio-reportedly-close-to-launch-yet-labels-still-have-to-sign/#p3n\">Read 3 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/04/apples-iradio-reportedly-close-to-launch-yet-labels-still-have-to-sign/?comments=1\">Comments</a></p><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=tRRS2GhiRC4:csn5cXfzbqI:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=tRRS2GhiR