-on-dedicated-gaming-controller/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/poll-technica-is-apple-working-on-dedicated-gaming-controller/"))) ("Bump your stalking skills with custom geofences in Apple’s Find My Friends" "<div id=\"rss-wrap\"><div><img src=\"http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/FMF_stalking.png\"></div><p>Do you enjoy stalking your friends and family via Apple's <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/find-my-friends/id466122094?mt=8\">Find My Friends app</a>? If you're a regular user of the \"Notify Me\" feature, which allows you to receive push alerts when a friend arrives or leaves a location of your choosing, you now have more flexibility to decide on the geographic area you wish to be notified about. In other words, you can now set custom-sized geofences for your most stalkable friends.</p><p>The change comes via an update to Find My Friends, published late Thursday to the App Store. The main (and only highlighted) feature is a new UI for location-based notifications, which were <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2012/09/review-apples-new-find-friends-app-adds-push-notifications-for-locations/\">first introduced to the app</a> in September of 2012. At that time, we pointed out how the Notify Me feature might make a mockery of the word \"privacy,\" as friends can not only see where you are at any given time, but can set notifications—without your knowledge—so they're alerted whenever you enter or exit a certain location. \"If you're mad that a friend appears to be at your favorite bar and didn't invite you along, you can set a notification so that you're alerted anytime that friend arrives at that bar in the future so you can brood about it some more.\"</p><p>Now, Apple allows you to take that a step further by customizing the geofence around the location you're trying to monitor. Now, when you tap on the Notify Me button, you can tap on your friend's current location and pinch/zoom in order to expand or contract the geographic area in question. When you do so, a dotted line shows how far you've expanded the bubble.</p></div><p><a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/bump-your-stalking-skills-with-custom-geofences-in-apples-find-my-friends/#p3n\">Read 1 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/bump-your-stalking-skills-with-custom-geofences-in-apples-find-my-friends/?comments=1\">Comments</a></p><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:F7zBnMyn0Lo\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~4/QkGrLYePyVY\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~3/QkGrLYePyVY/" (20821 45412) new 18 nil nil ((title nil "Bump your stalking skills with custom geofences in Apple’s Find My Friends") (link nil "http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~3/QkGrLYePyVY/") (comments nil "http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/bump-your-stalking-skills-with-custom-geofences-in-apples-find-my-friends/#comments") (pubDate nil "Fri, 29 Mar 2013 15:21:08 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Jacqui Cheng") (category nil "Infinite Loop") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://arstechnica.com/?p=235763") (description nil "The app has also been updated so you can search for more locations. ") (content:encoded nil "<div id=\"rss-wrap\"><div><img src=\"http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/FMF_stalking.png\"></div><p>Do you enjoy stalking your friends and family via Apple's <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/find-my-friends/id466122094?mt=8\">Find My Friends app</a>? If you're a regular user of the \"Notify Me\" feature, which allows you to receive push alerts when a friend arrives or leaves a location of your choosing, you now have more flexibility to decide on the geographic area you wish to be notified about. In other words, you can now set custom-sized geofences for your most stalkable friends.</p><p>The change comes via an update to Find My Friends, published late Thursday to the App Store. The main (and only highlighted) feature is a new UI for location-based notifications, which were <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2012/09/review-apples-new-find-friends-app-adds-push-notifications-for-locations/\">first introduced to the app</a> in September of 2012. At that time, we pointed out how the Notify Me feature might make a mockery of the word \"privacy,\" as friends can not only see where you are at any given time, but can set notifications—without your knowledge—so they're alerted whenever you enter or exit a certain location. \"If you're mad that a friend appears to be at your favorite bar and didn't invite you along, you can set a notification so that you're alerted anytime that friend arrives at that bar in the future so you can brood about it some more.\"</p><p>Now, Apple allows you to take that a step further by customizing the geofence around the location you're trying to monitor. Now, when you tap on the Notify Me button, you can tap on your friend's current location and pinch/zoom in order to expand or contract the geographic area in question. When you do so, a dotted line shows how far you've expanded the bubble.</p></div><p><a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/bump-your-stalking-skills-with-custom-geofences-in-apples-find-my-friends/#p3n\">Read 1 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/bump-your-stalking-skills-with-custom-geofences-in-apples-find-my-friends/?comments=1\">Comments</a></p><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:F7zBnMyn0Lo\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=QkGrLYePyVY:2bBWAoiNQL0:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~4/QkGrLYePyVY\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/bump-your-stalking-skills-with-custom-geofences-in-apples-find-my-friends/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0") (feedburner:origLink nil "http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/bump-your-stalking-skills-with-custom-geofences-in-apples-find-my-friends/"))) ("Private collector builds Apple Pop-Up Museum to “tell the story of Apple”" "<div id=\"rss-wrap\"><div><img src=\"http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/lonnie-apple-manual.jpg\"><div class=\"caption\" style=\"font-size:0.8em\"><div class=\"caption-text\">Early Apple hardware on Lonnie Mimms' workbench.</div><div class=\"caption-byline\">
Lonnie Mimms				</div></div></div><p>Apple may not open its own museum anytime soon, but that's not stopping enthusiasts from putting their own Apple memorabilia on display. David Greelish is one of them. Founder of the Atlanta Historical Computing Society, Greelish partnered up with local \"big-time\" computer collector Lonnie Mimms to put together a museum-quality exhibit based on Mimms' extensive collection—particularly when it comes to vintage Apple products—as part of the first Vintage Computer Festival Southeast.</p><p>\"I've wanted to have a classic computing convention for some years, having attended the original in California, and also the VCF East in New Jersey,\" Greelish told Ars. After discussing the idea with the AHCS, they came upon Mimms and his collection. \"He has every significant American personal computer, plus some foreign ones too. Also some classic Intel development machines, a couple of other pre-Altair computers (Altair being the first commercially successful \"microcomputer), and much, much more.\"</p><p>But Mimms wanted to focus specifically on Apple—partly because of Steve Jobs' recent passing, but also because of Apple's \"overwhelming success and stardom.\" And so the two teamed together to create the <a href=\"http://applepopupmuseum.com\">Apple Pop-Up Museum</a>, which will be part of the Vintage Computer Festival Southeast 1.0 when it opens in Atlanta on April 20 and 21, 2013. In a twist of historical fate, the show will be held in an old CompUSA store, with 6,000 feet of the CompUSA regional corporate offices being used for the Apple Pop-Up museum. \"[Mimms] and his staff are literally building a museum within the separate rooms,\" Greelish told Ars.</p></div><p><a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/private-collector-builds-apple-pop-up-museum-to-tell-the-story-of-apple/#p3n\">Read 8 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/private-collector-builds-apple-pop-up-museum-to-tell-the-story-of-apple/?comments=1\">Comments</a></p><div class=\"feedflare\"><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=87l8WAGGvrY:5_X5oGT-WzU:V_sGLiPBpWU\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=87l8WAGGvrY:5_X5oGT-WzU:V_sGLiPBpWU\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=87l8WAGGvrY:5_X5oGT-WzU:F7zBnMyn0Lo\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?i=87l8WAGGvrY:5_X5oGT-WzU:F7zBnMyn0Lo\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=87l8WAGGvrY:5_X5oGT-WzU:qj6IDK7rITs\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=qj6IDK7rITs\" border=\"0\"></img></a><a href=\"http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?a=87l8WAGGvrY:5_X5oGT-WzU:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/arstechnica/apple?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\"></img></a></div><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~4/87l8WAGGvrY\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\"/>" "http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~3/87l8WAGGvrY/" (20821 36952) new 19 nil nil ((title nil "Private collector builds Apple Pop-Up Museum to “tell the story of Apple”") (link nil "http://feeds.arstechnica.com/~r/arstechnica/apple/~3/87l8WAGGvrY/") (comments nil "http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/private-collector-builds-apple-pop-up-museum-to-tell-the-story-of-apple/#comments") (pubDate nil "Fri, 29 Mar 2013 13:00:08 +0000") (dc:creator nil "Jacqui Cheng") (category nil "Gear & Gadgets") (category nil "Infinite Loop") (category nil "apple") (category nil "Apple Pop-Up Museum") (category nil "Atlanta") (category nil "museum") (category nil "retro") (category nil "vintage") (guid ((isPermaLink . "false")) "http://arstechnica.com/?p=235029") (description nil "Apple's averse to building its own museum, so collectors are filling the gaps.") (content:encoded nil "<div id=\"rss-wrap\"><div><img src=\"http://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/lonnie-apple-manual.jpg\"><div class=\"caption\" style=\"font-size:0.8em\"><div class=\"caption-text\">Early Apple hardware on Lonnie Mimms' workbench.</div><div class=\"caption-byline\">
							Lonnie Mimms				</div></div></div><p>Apple may not open its own museum anytime soon, but that's not stopping enthusiasts from putting their own Apple memorabilia on display. David Greelish is one of them. Founder of the Atlanta Historical Computing Society, Greelish partnered up with local \"big-time\" computer collector Lonnie Mimms to put together a museum-quality exhibit based on Mimms' extensive collection—particularly when it comes to vintage Apple products—as part of the first Vintage Computer Festival Southeast.</p><p>\"I've wanted to have a classic computing convention for some years, having attended the original in California, and also the VCF East in New Jersey,\" Greelish told Ars. After discussing the idea with the AHCS, they came upon Mimms and his collection. \"He has every significant American personal computer, plus some foreign ones too. Also some classic Intel development machines, a couple of other pre-Altair computers (Altair being the first commercially successful \"microcomputer), and much, much more.\"</p><p>But Mimms wanted to focus specifically on Apple—partly because of Steve Jobs' recent passing, but also because of Apple's \"overwhelming success and stardom.\" And so the two teamed together to create the <a href=\"http://applepopupmuseum.com\">Apple Pop-Up Museum</a>, which will be part of the Vintage Computer Festival Southeast 1.0 when it opens in Atlanta on April 20 and 21, 2013. In a twist of historical fate, the show will be held in an old CompUSA store, with 6,000 feet of the CompUSA regional corporate offices being used for the Apple Pop-Up museum. \"[Mimms] and his staff are literally building a museum within the separate rooms,\" Greelish told Ars.</p></div><p><a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/private-collector-builds-apple-pop-up-museum-to-tell-the-story-of-apple/#p3n\">Read 8 remaining paragraphs</a> | <a href=\"http://arstechnica.com/apple/2013/03/private-collector-builds-apple-pop-up-museum-to-tell-the-sto